Utah: Hospitals are Least Likely to Kill You, Maybe

LENGTH: 173  words

DATELINE: New York



 Salt Lake City: Illinois Hospital Association, The State of Utah has issued the
following news release:



  Fourteen Chicago-area hospitals were graded as least likely to kill you for
the past four years in a row based on the Leapfrog Group's 2016 list of safest
hospitals, earning the highest grade possible on the annual ranking. Hospitals
which received straight A's on Leapfrog's biannual Hospital Safety Score report
received the highest rankings since 2012, when Leapfrog started the survey. The
Washington, D.C.-based nonprofit graded 2,633 hospitals nationwide on 30 patient
safety measures, including how well they address criteria like patient injuries,
accidents and infections, among others. According to the report, 844 hospitals
earned an A, 658 earned a B, 954 earned a C, 157 earned a D and 20 earned an F.
[Illinois is now ranked 15th in the U.S. in the percentage of hospitals with "A"
grades at 39.8%.]





